WEBVTT

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:21.500
Maintaining some degree of website accessibility is a legal requirement

00:00:21.500 --> 00:00:25.500
in many countries, including the UK and USA.

00:00:25.500 --> 00:00:29.500
But more than that, it's about creating more inclusive online spaces for everyone.

00:00:29.500 --> 00:00:33.500
The Web Content Accessibility Guidelines are designed to make content

00:00:33.500 --> 00:00:37.500
on desktops, laptops, tablets, and mobile devices more accessible

00:00:37.500 --> 00:00:42.000
to a wider range of people, especially those with disabilities,

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:46.000
including blindness and low vision, deafness and hearing loss,

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:50.000
limited movement, speech disabilities, photosensitivity,

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:53.500
and some learning disabilities like dyslexia.

00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:57.500
The guidelines state that content and user interfaces should be

00:00:57.500 --> 00:01:02.000
perceivable, operable, understandable, robust, and reliable.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.500
But what do these principles mean in practice?

00:01:05.500 --> 00:01:10.000
Perceivable. Making your content perceivable means improving visibility

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:14.000
and readability through clear and consistent headers

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:18.000
that enhance the user experience.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.500
Use descriptive alt text for images and consider screen readers.

00:01:22.500 --> 00:01:27.000
Operable. An operable navigation and user interface means users can

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:31.500
navigate with a keyboard alone, without using a mouse or trackpad.

00:01:31.500 --> 00:01:35.500
They have time to read and interact with your content,

00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:39.000
understand their position on the page,

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.000
and easily move through your website,

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:46.500
finding all the information they need.

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:51.000
Understandable. It’s important to make your content and the user journey

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.500
as easy as possible to understand.

00:01:55.500 --> 00:02:00.000
Use clear and simple language, be consistent throughout navigation,

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:04.500
and provide meaningful error messages to minimize confusion.

00:02:04.500 --> 00:02:09.000
Robust and reliable. When building robust and reliable websites,

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:13.500
it’s important to ensure compatibility with various browsers

00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:17.500
and assistive technologies.

00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:22.000
This allows users to access your content regardless of the tools they use.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.500
This means both future-proofing and iterating for the latest technology.

00:02:26.500 --> 00:02:31.000
Once you understand these principles, you can start to implement them

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:35.000
by following the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines linked in the description.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.500
Then you can assess how well your site conforms.

00:02:38.500 --> 00:02:42.000
Level A is basic accessibility.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:45.500
Level AA is strong accessibility.

00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:49.000
Level AAA is excellent accessibility.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:53.500
Level AA is the standard all websites should be aiming for,

00:02:53.500 --> 00:02:58.000
while AAA criteria are generally considered more applicable

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.500
to specific circumstances and content types.

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:06.500
It’s unlikely you’ll need to tick every AAA box,

00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:10.500
but some may be relevant to your business or users.

00:03:10.500 --> 00:03:15.000
So next time you start a website project or update your site,

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:19.500
be sure to check whether it meets user expectations

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:23.500
and accessibility guidelines.

